4–1241","1180–1241":"1180–1241","1190–1241":"1190–1241","1215–1243":"1215–1243","1220–1309":"1220–1309","1155–1184":"1155–1184","1160–1184":"1160–1184","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","Abt 1215":"about 1215","1241":"1241","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","Abt 1220":"about 1220","1155":"1155","1243":"1243","1309":"1309","Of, Wotton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wotton Underwood, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Hallaton, Leicestershire, England":"Hallaton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Grenville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Grainville-la-Teinturière in Seine-Maritime, France."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Eustace","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French form of the Late Greek names <i>Eustakhios</i> and <i>Eustathios</i>. These were evidently of separate origin, the former derived from <i>eu</i> ‘well, good’ + <i>stakhys</i> ‘grapes’, the latter from <i>eu</i> + <i>stēnai</i> ‘to stand’. However, the tradition is very confused. The name was introduced in this form to Britain by the Normans, among whom it was popular as a result of the fame of  St Eustace , a Norman nobleman who was said to have been converted to Christianity by the vision of a crucifix between the antlers of the stag he was hunting."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":31,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":40,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Eustace de Grenville was born in 1184, in Hallaton, Leicestershire, England, his father, Adam de Grenville I, was 29 and his mother, Isabel de Sancta-Fide, was 24. He married Joan Arsic. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1241, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1184–1241":"1184–1241","1180–1241":"1180–1241","1190–1241":"1190–1241","1215–1243":"1215–1243","1220–1309":"1220–1309","1155–1184":"1155–1184","1160–1184":"1160–1184","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","Abt 1215":"umbes 1215","1241":"1241","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1155":"1155","1243":"1243","1309":"1309","Of, Wotton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wotton Underwood, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hall